---
import CalculatorLayout from '../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro';
import PaycheckCalculator from '../components/calculators/PaycheckCalculator';
import { TAX_YEAR } from '../lib/constants';

const title = `Salary Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}: Annual Take-Home Pay Breakdown`;
const description = `Enter your annual salary and see what you actually take home in ${TAX_YEAR}. Get a detailed breakdown by pay period — monthly, biweekly, and weekly — after all taxes.`;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How do I calculate my annual take-home pay?',
    answer: `Start with your gross annual salary, then subtract federal income tax, state income tax (if applicable), Social Security tax (6.2% up to $176,100), Medicare tax (1.45%), and any pre-tax deductions like 401(k) or health insurance premiums. The remainder is your net annual take-home pay.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the difference between gross salary and net salary?',
    answer: `Gross salary is your total annual compensation before any deductions. Net salary (take-home pay) is what you actually receive after federal taxes, state taxes, FICA (Social Security + Medicare), and pre-tax deductions are subtracted. Depending on your state and tax bracket, net pay is typically 60%-80% of gross.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'How much of my salary goes to taxes?',
    answer: `For ${TAX_YEAR}, the average American pays about 22%-35% of their salary in total taxes, depending on income level, filing status, and state. This includes federal income tax (10%-37%), FICA taxes (7.65%), and state income tax (0%-13.3%). Higher earners face higher effective tax rates due to progressive brackets.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'Does my salary calculator include state taxes?',
    answer: `Yes. Our salary calculator includes all 50 states plus DC. Select your state from the dropdown to see the correct state income tax applied. Nine states (Alaska, Florida, Nevada, New Hampshire, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Washington, and Wyoming) have no state income tax on wages.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'How does a 401(k) contribution affect my salary?',
    answer: `Traditional 401(k) contributions are deducted from your gross salary before federal and state income taxes are calculated, reducing your taxable income and your tax bill. However, 401(k) contributions do not reduce FICA taxes. For example, a $10,000 401(k) contribution on a $75,000 salary means you're only taxed on $65,000 for income tax purposes.`,
  },
  {
    question: `What are the ${TAX_YEAR} federal tax brackets for salary income?`,
    answer: `For ${TAX_YEAR}, Single filers pay: 10% on income up to $11,925; 12% up to $48,475; 22% up to $103,350; 24% up to $197,300; 32% up to $250,525; 35% up to $626,350; and 37% above that. These rates apply to taxable income after the standard deduction ($15,700 for Single, $31,400 for Married Filing Jointly).`,
  },
];

const relatedCalculators = [
  { title: 'Paycheck Calculator', href: '/', desc: 'Calculate per-paycheck take-home' },
  { title: 'Hourly Pay Calculator', href: '/hourly-paycheck-calculator/', desc: 'Convert hourly rate to annual' },
  { title: 'Income Tax Calculator', href: '/income-tax-calculator/', desc: 'Federal + state tax breakdown' },
  { title: 'Self-Employment Tax', href: '/self-employment-tax-calculator/', desc: '1099 and freelancer taxes' },
  { title: 'Bonus Tax Calculator', href: '/bonus-tax-calculator/', desc: 'How much tax on your bonus' },
];

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'WebApplication',
  name: `Salary Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}`,
  description,
  url: 'https://truetakehomepay.com/salary-calculator',
  applicationCategory: 'FinanceApplication',
  operatingSystem: 'Any',
  offers: {
    '@type': 'Offer',
    price: '0',
    priceCurrency: 'USD',
  },
  inLanguage: 'en-US',
};
---

<CalculatorLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  h1={`Salary Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}`}
  intro={`Enter your annual salary to see a complete breakdown of your take-home pay after federal and state taxes, FICA, and deductions. Updated for ${TAX_YEAR} tax brackets.`}
  faqs={faqs}
  relatedCalculators={relatedCalculators}
  schema={schema}
  sources={`IRS Rev. Proc. 2025-11 (${TAX_YEAR} federal tax brackets and standard deductions), SSA.gov (Social Security wage base $176,100), state revenue department publications. Last updated for tax year ${TAX_YEAR}.`}
>
  <PaycheckCalculator
    client:load
    defaultPayFrequency="annual"
    defaultGross={75000}
  />
  <Fragment slot="content">
    <section class="border-t border-slate-200 px-4 py-16 dark:border-slate-800 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose prose-slate dark:prose-invert mx-auto max-w-3xl">
        <h2 id="how-salary-structures-work">How Salary Structures Work in the United States</h2>
        <p>When you accept a job offer with an annual salary, the number on your offer letter represents your gross compensation before any deductions reach your paycheck. That figure, whether it is $45,000 or $150,000, is the starting point of a calculation that involves federal tax withholding, state income taxes, Social Security contributions, Medicare premiums, and any voluntary deductions your employer offers. Understanding the mechanics behind this process is the single most important step toward taking control of your personal finances.</p>
        <p>Most salaried positions in the United States pay employees on a biweekly or semi-monthly schedule. A biweekly schedule produces 26 paychecks per year, while semi-monthly payroll results in 24. The distinction matters more than people realize. On a biweekly schedule, two months each year contain three paydays instead of two, which can create a windfall effect that savvy budgeters use for extra savings or debt repayment. If you earn $78,000 annually on a biweekly schedule, each gross paycheck comes to $3,000 before deductions. On a semi-monthly schedule, that same salary yields $3,250 per paycheck. Neither option changes your annual tax liability, but the timing affects cash flow planning throughout the year.</p>
        <p>Your employer is legally required to withhold federal income tax from each paycheck based on the information you provide on IRS Form W-4. The W-4 was redesigned in 2020 to eliminate the old allowance system and replace it with a more straightforward approach that asks about additional income, dependents, and extra withholding. If you filled out your W-4 years ago and never updated it, your withholding may not reflect your current situation. Married employees who both work, for instance, often find that they owe money at tax time because each employer withholds as if the employee is the sole earner in the household.</p>

        <h2 id="salary-negotiation-insights">What Most People Get Wrong About Salary Negotiation</h2>
        <p>Salary negotiation is one of the few financial decisions where a single conversation can add tens of thousands of dollars to your lifetime earnings. Research from Carnegie Mellon University found that employees who negotiate their starting salary earn an average of $600,000 more over a 40-year career compared to those who accept the first offer. Yet surveys consistently show that more than half of American workers have never negotiated their pay.</p>
        <p>The reluctance to negotiate stems from several misconceptions. Many candidates believe that the initial offer is final and that pushing back will cause the employer to rescind it. In practice, employers expect negotiation and often leave room in their budget for it. A survey by Robert Half found that 70% of hiring managers expect candidates to counter their first offer. The risk of losing the offer entirely is extraordinarily low, as companies invest significant time and resources into selecting a candidate before extending an offer.</p>
        <p>When preparing to negotiate, the most effective strategy is to research salary data for your specific role, industry, and geographic market. Resources like the Bureau of Labor Statistics Occupational Employment and Wage Statistics program publish median salaries for hundreds of job classifications across every metropolitan area in the country. Armed with this data, you can frame your counter-offer around market value rather than personal need, which employers find far more compelling. Instead of saying you need more money, demonstrate that comparable roles in your market command a higher salary and explain the specific skills or experience you bring that justify the higher end of the range.</p>
        <p>Beyond base salary, consider negotiating other elements of your compensation package. Signing bonuses, equity grants, additional vacation days, remote work flexibility, professional development budgets, and accelerated review timelines all have monetary value. Some employers find it easier to offer a $5,000 signing bonus than to increase base salary by the same amount, because the bonus is a one-time expense that does not compound through future raises and does not set a precedent for other employees in the same role.</p>

        <h2 id="salary-vs-hourly">The Salary Versus Hourly Debate</h2>
        <p>The choice between salaried and hourly compensation involves trade-offs that go well beyond the paycheck amount. Salaried employees receive the same pay regardless of hours worked, which provides income stability and makes budgeting straightforward. However, this stability comes with a catch that many workers do not fully appreciate until they experience it firsthand. Salaried employees classified as exempt under the Fair Labor Standards Act do not receive overtime pay, no matter how many hours they work in a given week. An exempt employee earning $65,000 who routinely works 50 hours per week is effectively earning less per hour than their salary implies.</p>
        <p>To put this in perspective, a $65,000 salary based on a standard 40-hour week translates to approximately $31.25 per hour. But if that same employee works 50 hours per week consistently, the effective hourly rate drops to $25.00. If you are evaluating a salaried position, it is worth asking during the interview process about typical weekly hours for the role. Some industries, particularly finance, consulting, and law, are known for demanding 55 to 70 hours per week from salaried professionals, which dramatically reduces the effective hourly rate. You can use our <a href="/hourly-paycheck-calculator/">hourly paycheck calculator</a> to compare what those hours would yield at overtime rates.</p>
        <p>Hourly workers, on the other hand, benefit from the FLSA requirement that non-exempt employees receive time-and-a-half pay for hours worked beyond 40 in a workweek. An hourly worker earning $25 per hour who works 50 hours in a week earns $25 for the first 40 hours and $37.50 for each of the 10 overtime hours, bringing the weekly gross to $1,375 instead of $1,250. Over a full year with consistent overtime, this adds up to a meaningful increase. Our <a href="/overtime-pay-calculator/">overtime pay calculator</a> can help you see exactly how overtime hours affect your take-home pay after taxes.</p>

        <h2 id="interpreting-salary-breakdown">How to Read and Interpret Your Salary Breakdown</h2>
        <p>Your pay stub contains a wealth of information, but many employees glance at the net pay amount and ignore the rest. Taking the time to understand each line item will help you identify errors, plan for taxes, and make smarter decisions about benefits enrollment.</p>
        <p>The first section of your pay stub shows gross earnings. For salaried employees, this is your annual salary divided by the number of pay periods. If you see a discrepancy between your expected gross and the actual amount, check whether your employer prorates the first or last paycheck of your employment or adjusts for mid-period start dates.</p>
        <p>Federal income tax withholding is typically the largest deduction. The amount withheld depends on your taxable wages (gross minus pre-tax deductions), your filing status, and any adjustments on your W-4. If you received a large tax refund last year, you may be over-withholding, which means you are giving the government an interest-free loan from every paycheck. Conversely, if you owed money at tax time, you may need to increase your withholding to avoid a penalty. The <a href="/income-tax-calculator/">income tax calculator</a> on this site can help you estimate your annual federal and state tax liability so you can adjust your W-4 accordingly.</p>
        <p>Social Security tax is withheld at a flat rate of 6.2% on wages up to the annual cap, which is $176,100 for 2025. Once your year-to-date earnings exceed this threshold, Social Security withholding stops for the remainder of the year. If you earn above the cap, you will notice slightly larger paychecks in the last few months of the year. Medicare tax is withheld at 1.45% on all wages with no cap, and high earners pay an Additional Medicare Tax of 0.9% on wages above $200,000 for single filers.</p>
        <p>State income tax withholding varies enormously depending on where you live. If you reside in one of the nine states with no income tax on wages, including Texas, Florida, and Washington, your paycheck will be noticeably larger than someone earning the same salary in a high-tax state like California or New York. The difference can be substantial. A worker earning $80,000 in Texas takes home roughly $3,000 to $5,000 more per year than an identical earner in California, purely from the state tax difference. Our <a href="/take-home-pay-calculator/">take-home pay calculator</a> lets you compare net pay across different states to quantify this effect.</p>

        <h2 id="regional-salary-differences">Regional Salary Differences and Cost of Living</h2>
        <p>A $100,000 salary in San Francisco does not go nearly as far as $100,000 in Nashville or Raleigh. Geographic pay differences are driven by local cost of living, state and local tax rates, and regional labor market conditions. The Bureau of Labor Statistics publishes regional price parities that show how the cost of goods and services varies across metropolitan areas. As of recent data, the San Francisco metro area has prices roughly 18% above the national average, while cities like Memphis and Oklahoma City fall 10% to 12% below the national average.</p>
        <p>Housing costs are the primary driver of cost-of-living differences. In the San Jose metro area, the median home price exceeds $1.4 million, while in cities like Indianapolis or Columbus, the median sits below $300,000. This means that a worker earning $120,000 in San Jose may have a lower standard of living than someone earning $75,000 in Indianapolis, even though the gross salary is 60% higher. The <a href="/cost-of-living-calculator/">cost of living calculator</a> on this site can help you understand how far your salary stretches in different parts of the country.</p>
        <p>Remote work has fundamentally changed the salary geography equation. During and after the pandemic, many companies adopted location-based pay bands that adjust salaries based on where the employee lives. An employee doing the same job from Boise, Idaho might receive 15% to 25% less than a colleague working from the company's headquarters in New York City. Whether this is fair is debatable, but it is increasingly common. When evaluating a remote job offer, consider the total package, including the salary in the context of your local cost of living, state tax burden, and benefits value.</p>

        <h2 id="benefits-total-compensation">The Hidden Value of Benefits in Your Total Compensation</h2>
        <p>Your salary is only one piece of your total compensation. Employer-sponsored benefits often add 30% to 40% to the value of your base salary, though most employees dramatically underestimate their worth. Understanding the full picture is essential when comparing job offers or evaluating whether your current compensation is competitive.</p>
        <p>Health insurance is typically the most valuable benefit. The average employer-sponsored health plan costs over $8,400 per year for individual coverage and more than $23,000 for family coverage, according to the Kaiser Family Foundation. Employers cover roughly 80% of the premium for individual plans and about 70% for family plans, meaning your employer may be contributing $6,700 to $16,000 per year toward your health insurance alone. This is effectively invisible compensation that you would need to purchase on the open market if you were self-employed. You can explore the tax implications of self-employment using our <a href="/self-employment-tax-calculator/">self-employment tax calculator</a>.</p>
        <p>Retirement benefits represent another major component. If your employer offers a 401(k) match, that match is free money that compounds over your career. A common match structure is 50% of employee contributions up to 6% of salary. On a $75,000 salary, if you contribute 6% ($4,500), your employer adds $2,250. Over a 30-year career with 7% average annual returns, that employer match alone would grow to approximately $213,000. The <a href="/401k-calculator/">401(k) calculator</a> can help you model how different contribution and match scenarios play out over time.</p>
        <p>Paid time off, life insurance, disability insurance, tuition reimbursement, commuter benefits, and employee stock purchase plans all add additional value. When you are evaluating a job offer, request a total compensation statement from the employer that itemizes the value of each benefit. This allows you to make an apples-to-apples comparison between offers, rather than fixating solely on the salary number. A position offering $85,000 with generous benefits may be worth more than a $95,000 offer with minimal benefits, once you account for out-of-pocket costs you would incur replacing those benefits on your own.</p>
        <p>Understanding your salary is not just about knowing the number on your offer letter. It is about grasping the full mechanics of how that number is reduced by taxes, enhanced by benefits, and influenced by where you live and how you negotiate. Use this salary calculator alongside the other tools on our site to build a complete picture of your financial situation and make smarter decisions about your career and money.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>
</CalculatorLayout>
